) across different jurisdictions in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the current legal status of VAD in Australia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Legal in some, but not all, states and territories in Australia","Legal across Australia","Illegal in all states and territories","Legal in Victoria and Western Australia only","Legal in New South Wales only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that voluntary assisted dying (VAD) is \u003Cstrong\u003Elegal in some, but not all, states and territories in Australia\u003C/strong\u003E. As of January 2025, all Australian states have passed legislation permitting VAD. However, it remains unavailable in The Northern Territory and Australian Capital Territory, though VAD laws have been passed in the Australian Capital Territory and will commence on 3 November 2025.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEach state has its own specific eligibility criteria and safeguards in their legislation. Healthcare practitioners maintain the right to conscientiously object to participating in VAD, though they must not impede access to information about legal end-of-life options.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Voluntary assisted dying is legal in all Australian states but not in territories as of January 2025.","Each state has its own specific legislation and eligibility criteria for voluntary assisted dying .","Healthcare practitioners have the right to conscientiously object to participating in voluntary assisted dying."],"references":["Queensland University of Technology. End of life law in Australia: Voluntary assisted dying [Internet]. 2025 [cited 2025 Jan 17]. Available from: https://end-of-life.qut.edu.au/assisteddying","End of Life Directions for Aged Care. Voluntary Assisted Dying [Internet]. 2025 [cited 2025 Jan 17]. Available from: https://www.eldac.com.au/Our-Toolkits/End-of-Life-Law/